# Hourly Price Dynamics in the Greek Day-Ahead Market
## January 2025 Exploratory Analysis

This notebook presents an exploratory analysis of hourly price formation in the Greek Day-Ahead Market (DAM) for January 2025.

The goal is to examine how electricity prices relate to:

- System Load
- Renewable generation (RES)
- Net Load (Load − RES)
- Residual demand ramps

The analysis is based on 744 hourly observations.

## 1. Imports

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.style.use("seaborn-v0_8-whitegrid")

## 2. Load Processed Dataset

The dataset contains merged hourly observations for:

- MCP (Market Clearing Price)
- Load
- RES
- Net Load

## 3. Derived Variables

We compute hourly residual demand ramps:

Ramp = Δ(Net Load)

df["ramp"] = df.groupby("date")["net_load"].diff()

## 4. Hourly Aggregation

hourly = df.groupby("hour")[["MCP","load","net_load"]].mean()
ramp_hourly = df.groupby("hour")["ramp"].mean()

## 5. Average MCP by Hour

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.plot(hourly.index, hourly["MCP"], linewidth=2)
plt.xlabel("Hour")
plt.ylabel("Average MCP (€/MWh)")
plt.title("Average MCP by Hour – January 2025")
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

## 6. Load vs Net Load

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.plot(hourly.index, hourly["load"], linewidth=2)
plt.plot(hourly.index, hourly["net_load"], linewidth=2)
plt.xlabel("Hour")
plt.ylabel("MW")
plt.title("Load vs Net Load – January 2025")
plt.legend(["Load","Net Load"])
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

## 7. Average Net Load Ramp by Hour

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.plot(ramp_hourly.index, ramp_hourly, linewidth=2)
plt.xlabel("Hour")
plt.ylabel("Average Net Load Ramp (MW)")
plt.title("Average Net Load Ramp by Hour")
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

## 8. MCP vs Net Load Ramp

plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.scatter(df["ramp"], df["MCP"], alpha=0.5)
plt.xlabel("Net Load Ramp (MW)")
plt.ylabel("MCP (€/MWh)")
plt.title("MCP vs Net Load Ramp")
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

## 9. Correlation Analysis

df[["MCP","load","net_load","ramp"]].corr()

## 10. Key Observations

- MCP correlates with Load (~0.63)
- MCP correlates with Net Load (~0.60)
- Peak prices occur before peak load
- Positive residual demand ramps show moderate correlation with MCP (~0.40)

These observations suggest that hourly price formation in the Greek DAM is influenced not only by absolute demand levels but also by system transitions and ramp dynamics.

Electricity markets respond to system stress — not just peak demand.
